	<h2>Types of Hearing Aid Batteries</h2>

	<h3>Disposable Zinc-Air Batteries</h3>
	<p>
		Disposable, or "button," batteries have been used in hearing aids for many
		years. They provide stable power and come in several sizes, each marked
		with a color for easy identification:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Size 10 – Yellow</li>
		<li>Size 312 – Brown</li>
		<li>Size 13 – Orange</li>
		<li>Size 675 – Blue</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		These batteries are activated once you remove the small protective tab.
		After removing the battery from the package, it's best to let the battery
		sit for a few minutes before inserting it into your hearing aid. This brief
		waiting period allows the battery to fully activate so it can deliver its
		maximum power and performance.
	</p>

	<h3>Rechargeable Lithium-Ion Batteries</h3>
	<p>
		Most modern hearing aids now use built-in rechargeable lithium-ion
		batteries, which offer all-day power without the need to handle or replace
		small batteries. Many patients find this option especially helpful if they
		prefer a simpler routine or have dexterity or vision challenges.
	</p>
	<p>
		Rechargeables are also environmentally friendly, as they eliminate the need
		for frequent disposable battery changes.
	</p>

	<h3>Silver-Zinc Rechargeable Batteries</h3>
	<p>
		Some older hearing aid models still use removable silver-zinc rechargeable
		batteries. While these are less common in today's devices, our audiologists
		are fully equipped to support and service these systems if your hearing
		aids use them.
	</p>

	<h2>Which Battery Is Right for You?</h2>
	<p>
		The best battery option really depends on your individual hearing aids and
		your day-to-day lifestyle. When helping you decide, we consider things
		like:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>The specific model of your hearing aids</li>
		<li>Your daily routine and listening environments</li>
		<li>Your comfort level with handling small batteries or devices</li>
		<li>How many hours per day you typically wear your hearing aids</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		There's no one-size-fits-all answer. What works best is what fits most
		comfortably and consistently into your life.
	</p>
	<p>
		If you're ever unsure, our audiologist is here to walk you through the
		options and help you choose the solution that feels the most convenient,
		reliable, and easy for you to use every day.
	</p>

	<h2>Tips to Make Batteries Last Longer</h2>

	<h3>For Disposable Batteries</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>After removing the tab, wait five minutes before inserting</li>
		<li>Store batteries in a cool, dry place</li>
		<li>Open the battery door at night to reduce moisture</li>
		<li>Keep batteries clean and dry</li>
		<li>Carry spares in their original packaging</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>For Rechargeable Batteries</h3>
	<ul>
		<li>Charge them overnight so they're ready each morning</li>
		<li>Use the charger designed for your hearing aids</li>
		<li>Keep devices and charger away from moisture and extreme heat</li>
		<li>Turn off your hearing aids when not in use</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>How to Know When to Change Your Battery</h2>
	<p>
		Your hearing aids may alert you with a beep, a spoken reminder, or a
		flashing light when power is low. You might also notice:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Weak or fading sound</li>
		<li>Distortion</li>
		<li>Sound cutting in and out</li>
		<li>Devices turning off unexpectedly</li>
	</ul>
	<p>Often, a fresh battery or full recharge solves the issue.</p>

	<h2>Troubleshooting Battery Problems</h2>
	<p>If your hearing aids stop working, try checking:</p>
	<ul>
		<li>Is the battery the right size and properly inserted?</li>
		<li>Is the battery door fully closed?</li>
		<li>Are the battery contacts clean?</li>
		<li>Is the battery fresh or fully charged?</li>
	</ul>
	<p>
		If you've checked these steps and still have concerns, bring your devices
		to your hearing aid provider. Commonwealth Audiology offers professional
		hearing aid care and maintenance in Georgetown, KY.
	</p>

	<h2>Frequently Asked Questions About Hearing Aid Batteries</h2>
	<Accordion>
		<AccordionItem title="Which type lasts longer?">
			<p>
				Disposable hearing aid batteries typically last about 3–10 days,
				depending on the size of the battery and how often your hearing aids
				are used. Rechargeable batteries are designed to last all day on a
				single charge and usually only need to be replaced every few years.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Are rechargeable batteries better for the environment?">
			<p>
				Yes. Rechargeable systems significantly reduce the number of
				disposable batteries used over time, making them a more environmentally
				friendly option.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Can I switch my hearing aids from disposable to rechargeable?">
			<p>
				It depends on the model. Some hearing aids can be upgraded to
				rechargeable systems, while others are built for only one battery type.
				Our audiologists can evaluate your devices and let you know what
				options are available for you.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="Do cold temperatures affect batteries?">
			<p>
				Yes. Exposure to extreme cold can shorten battery life and impact
				performance. To help maintain reliability, it's best to keep your
				hearing aids and spare batteries at room temperature whenever possible.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
		<AccordionItem title="What should I do with old disposable batteries?">
			<p>
				Used hearing aid batteries should be properly recycled whenever
				possible. Many local pharmacies, hardware stores, and recycling centers
				accept them for safe disposal.
			</p>
		</AccordionItem>
	</Accordion>

